post_text:
Delphos FFA Members Have ‚ÄúBANNER‚Äù year at 2020 Allen County Fair

Delphos FFA members‚Äô hard work throughout the past year was rewarded as many of them were successful at the Allen County Fair. The chapter was represented very well as over 70 members exhibited shop and livestock projects. Delphos FFA was well represented with members placing at the top in their respective livestock classes. Also, several members were placed at the top in showmanship with their respective species.

The chapter was awarded several top places in the shop area as well. The projects that FFA members exhibit at the fair are the result of numerous hours of hard work and dedication. While preparing for the fair, members practice and improve the life skills such as responsibility, time management, decision making, cooperation, team work, and others. This is just another example of how the FFA and Agricultural Education help prepare students for a successful future.

Delphos Jefferson High School

The incoming freshmen get new chrome books each year that follow them through high school. Due to COVID, the shipment was moved from early August to late September, putting a strain on our reserves for the freshmen and K-12 DDA online students. Thank you to the parents, students, and staff for the patience!

The CLASS of 2020 ROCK arrived and found a home in front of the high school. It is a great tribute to the sacrifices of the class. Thank you to all the people and businesses that had a hand in making this happen!

The success of a reopening depends on the actions and reactions of those impacted. I am VERY PROUD of the students and staff as they adjusted to our plans and preparations for the known and unknown!

This is made possible with our amazing patient and positive parents. Scheduling, DDA set up, and chrome books are still finishing up for some and I appreciate, again, your patience. THANK you parents!

Mr. Brinkman

REGISTRATION and PICTURE UPDATES
Monday - Thursday August 3rd - 6th
9-11:30AM and 12:30-2:30 PM

RETURNING FORMS/ SCHOOL PICTURES WILL ALL TAKE PLACE IN THE CAREER CENTER
All required paperwork will be returned in the Career Center. Students and parent(s) will enter the Career Center to return paperwork and have the opportunity to pay fees. Paying by CREDIT CARD is an option this year.

PICTURES will be taken EVERYDAY during registration M-TH. After paperwork is returned, students will take photos for school. ALL Seniors (Vantage or DJHS) are required to get a picture, wear a shirt and tie for men and dress or blouse top for women. There are no obligations to purchase.

NOTES: Social distancing and masks will be in effect. There will be no walking the hallways or classrooms.

CONTACT Ms Kerner at kkerner@delphoscityschools.org or Elaine Rode at erode@delphoscityschools.org to set up an appointment to discuss schedule related changes. Friday is for new students or prior set appointments.

post_text:
Delphos Jefferson will host Rhodes State in providing College Credit Plus courses in the medical field. Delphos St Johns, Lincolnview, Ottoville, and Fort Jennings are members of the cohort that will give students the opportunity to earn a Patient Care Technician certification upon completion.

Below are the courses included in the Rhodes State STEM Public-Private Partnership.

BIO 1000 Basic Human Structure and Function
BHS 1390 Medical Terminology
BHS 1100 Patient Care Technician I
BHS 1160 Medical Law-Ethics Healthcare
BHS 1120 Patient Care Technician II

Because of COVID, classes will be taken online thru Rhodes with an IN PERSON 4 hour/week lab course in the career center. This is a year long program - students will still be taking traditional classes of Math, ELA, History, etc at the home school.

Students are encouraged to email Mr Brinkman to express interest and to learn more about the opportunity.

Sincerely,

Mr. Brinkman

Info from Rhodes State:

At Rhodes State College we have been working diligently to make as many changes as needed to help support our students and community during this time. One of the things that we have received numerous questions about is our annual Rhodesology summer youth camps. Due to the Coronavirus we are suspending any on campus camps but instead have implemented and are currently launching Rhodesology@Home. Take home camp kits with a weeks‚Äô worth of activities in hopes that kids can still experience the fun and educational ideas as they would on campus. Also giving kids a chance for something new right now when so many things are still in limbo for opening back up.

www.rhodesstate.edu/rhodesology

post_text:
A GREAT MOMENT!!

A few days ago, Jeffrey Caputo Jr. made a slide show of the graduating seniors that we put on the message board. Today, as I was leaving high school, I noticed a young man looking at our sign in front of the school. As we talked, he told me that he wanted to see the senior pictures.

Each year our high school students volunteer to go to Franklin and the Middle School to help teachers and engage with the young Wildcats. The young man, JACKSON OSBURN, was missing them, especially Rafael Montesano, and rode his bike over to find them.

As I left, I was struck by how cool it was and turned around for a picture. Jackson's actions demonstrate the impact our high school students have on the next generation.

What a great Wildcat Moment!!

Mr. Brinkman

Delphos Jefferson Softball
April 22 at 6:06 PM ¬∑

Since we are unable to play this season due to the closing of schools We would like to give our seniors a little shoutout! They have worked so hard the past fours year to get to their ‚ÄúFinal year‚Äù and deserve some fame!
***Share and like!!

Meet Jayla!

Favorite food: pancakes

Favorite movie: The Disney movie ‚ÄúHome‚Äù

Position: Centerfield

Years played: 4 years in high school, 11 years total

Miss the most: I will miss the little moments like inside jokes and practices, but I will definitely miss all of my wonderful teammates and coaches. I will miss everything about it.

Favorite memory: If I had to choose a few out of the many, many great memories I would say getting the first NWC win in 7 years by beating Ada, of course getting my foot stuck under the fence at Lima Senior, all of the Perry days, and playing 7 games in one week last year (best week of the year).

Future plans after graduation:University of Cincinnati studying Speech-Language Pathology

Dear Franklin Parents,

Franklin Elementary student work packets for the first three weeks of our Covid-19 closure can be turned in at the Main Entrance at Franklin Elementary (by the flagpole) on Wednesday, April 8; Thursday, April 9; and Friday, April 10 between 7:00 AM and 6:00 PM. There will be Grade Level Tubs in the entrance way. Simply place your student‚Äôs work in a plastic bag with their First and Last Name on it and place it in the appropriate grade level tub.

Please return any FRANKLIN SCHOOL LIBRARY Books your child has at home at this time as well. Please put the library books in the tub marked Library Books.

Please remember that the assigned papers in the packets were NOT optional and are required to be turned in as this is the way students will get credit for the days missed under the governor's current distance learning guidelines.

Thanks for your continued support and efforts during these challenging times. We are available to help with any questions you may have.

Robert Hohlbein
Franklin Elementary Principal
text:
Dear Franklin Parents,

Franklin Elementary student work packets for the first three weeks of our Covid-19 closure can be turned in at the Main Entrance at Franklin Elementary (by the flagpole) on Wednesday, April 8; Thursday, April 9; and Friday, April 10 between 7:00 AM and 6:00 PM. There will be Grade Level Tubs in the entrance way. Simply place your student‚Äôs work in a plastic bag with their First and Last Name on it and place it in the appropriate grade level tub.

Please return any FRANKLIN SCHOOL LIBRARY Books your child has at home at this time as well. Please put the library books in the tub marked Library Books.

Please remember that the assigned papers in the packets were NOT optional and are required to be turned in as this is the way students will get credit for the days missed under the governor's current distance learning guidelines.

Thanks for your continued support and efforts during these challenging times. We are available to help with any questions you may have.

Robert Hohlbein
Franklin Elementary Principal

post_text:
Dear Elementary Parents,

Delphos City Schools will be offering chromebooks to those elementary students in Grades 1-4 (PK and Kindergarten are not eligible to receive a chromebook) in need of an electronic device for the remainder of the covid-19 school shutdown. This is not mandatory. If your family already has an electronic device it is not necessary to use a school issued device. Due to the limited supply of chromebooks, we will limit chromebooks to one per family.

Franklin Elementary will be open Monday, April 6th from 9am - 12 noon and Tuesday, April 7th from 1pm - 4pm. Parents needing to borrow a chromebook will need to also sign the user agreement form. Students are not permitted to sign out a chromebook. Please be patient and practice required social distancing when coming to sign out a chromebook.

Douglas Westrick
Superintendent

post_text:
DELPHOS JEFFERSON HIGH SCHOOL

Dear Parents and Students,

Teachers will post one daily lesson, however, 2 of the lessons will include gradable assignments with a 24 hour due date. (Upper level courses can assume more than 2 assessments)These grades will be considered 4th quarter grades.

Teachers will make lessons using our acronym CLEAR when planning and assigning.

C = Continuation - the lessons flow with previous learning

L = Learnable - all students learn from the lesson

E = Empathy - reflect on student/family needs and concerns

A = Attainable - resources are available to complete lesson

R = Rigorous - the lesson challenges without overwhelming students

We continue to hold high expectations for teachers and students with a CLEAR understanding that student learning faces unique barriers and challenges. We also want to be aware of the challenges facing families helping with work while facing the overall anxieties during this time.

I ask that you communicate with teachers via email or send feedback or concerns to

cbrinkman@delphoscityschools.com

Sincerely,
Mr Brinkman

Please visit coronavirus.ohio.gov or call 1-833-4-ASK-OHD for the latest updates and information.

Attached are resources about stopping the spread of germs as well as a reminder of the symptoms associated with COVID-19.

Remember, you are not in this alone. We are all going to get through this TOGETHER!

Thank you to Julie Moore RDN, LD

Dear Parents and Guardians:
Delphos City Schools is working diligently to continue learning through this statewide school closure. Our special education intervention team is dedicated to providing online support through the closure process. Your patience is appreciated as we are in the planning stages at this time. More information will be provided as it becomes available, but please know that our team continues to hold your child's best interests in mind as we move forward through this unprecedented time. If your child's ETR/IEP/Service Plan meeting was to be held in the next several weeks, you will be contacted with further information. If you have further questions, please contact me at mrentz@delphoscityschools.org

Sincerely,

NMr Westrick - Superintendent

Mrs Rentz - Special Education Officer

AG. Department helps Delphos Athletic Departments

During a recent time of independant projects, junior and senior Agricultural students from the Delphos City Schools completed the construction of two track and field carts to carry starting blocks at competitions and practices.

This was an group effort from St. John's student Isaac Gable-center, Carson Kazee-Ft. Jennings student-left, and Braxton Scalf Jefferson student-right. They worked together in the shop on this project over the last couple of weeks.

This is just another example of how students in the Delphos City school communites come together for the benefit of all school communities. The project was funded by the athletic departments at Delphos St. John's and Delphos Jefferson.

The final project completed by the 5th and 6th graders in Mr. Spencer's pilot STEM class was building bridges out of toothpicks and then finding which design held the most weight. Students were placed in groups and given the jobs of accountant, materials manager, architect and builder. They were given a budget to work with and had to blueprint their designs and track spending to stay within budget (they even learned how to write checks.) Great job 5th and 6th grade!
